<Layout title="Origin Story">
  <h1>Origin Story</h1>

  <p>
    I grew up in a remote village, and my first interaction with technology happened pretty early in life. I still remember how much I loved watching Hollywood movies—especially Marvel ones. That world felt larger than life, and maybe that’s where my curiosity started.
  </p>

  <p>
    I got my first computer around 7th standard. Back then, it wasn’t about coding or building things—I just played games like GTA San Andreas, Need for Speed, IGI… and honestly, it was pure fun. But even then, technology felt fascinating. I wasn’t just playing—I liked tinkering around, clicking things, exploring how stuff worked.
  </p>

  <p>
    I didn’t have much technical exposure growing up. After high school, life got a bit messy. Things didn’t go the way I expected. I started preparing for government jobs—hoping for stability. I finished 12th, kept preparing, kept appearing for exams… and then COVID happened.
  </p>

  <p>
    During that time, something shifted. My obsession with computers came back stronger. I was enrolled in my bachelor's degree—first one and a half years were remote, and the rest were offline. Somewhere in that phase, I started getting serious about what I actually wanted to do with my life.
  </p>

  <p>
    Tech became my second option at first. I thought government jobs meant security—but honestly, it felt suffocating. I realized I needed more than that. I needed growth, money, and something that didn’t make me feel stuck.
  </p>

  <p>
    By the end of my graduation, I got an offer from TCS through mass recruitment. At the same time, I was exploring open-source communities, hanging out on Discord servers, and meeting people from all over the world. I made some really good online friends—Rajat is one of them.
  </p>

  <p>
    Getting my first job wasn’t easy—it took a lot of effort, a lot of setbacks—but I kept pushing through. There was a phase where I was unemployed for almost a year after graduation, and that was tough mentally. But that first job gave me clarity.
  </p>

  <p>
    I went all in. I worked hard, delivered results, and honestly—yeah, I dominated (Harvey Specter style 😄):
  </p>

